</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="786CB0AB9586DD25C4BFF8134A148BE9" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="432C84D70D5F25A830D8BC5FFE1571E6" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DA4CF5E4A43C0E81935649F0AA69C28F" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<taxonomicName id="334217CE1217E01C81DBABBEC9FA06D9" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 67 - 68" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pratensis">
<emphasis id="3C5EB415133697A0B42E86BAD596AFD9" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Poa pratensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subsp. 
<emphasis id="207C41BEFE1BA3A633807C36588E66B4" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">alpigena</emphasis>
is circumboreal and native to the New World in the arctic, alpine, subalpine, and boreal forests (
<bibRefCitation id="71FA61555F5EEA83A70CBDD7AACA039E" author="Soreng, RJ" journalOrPublisher="Madrono" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="B50" refString="Soreng, RJ, 2007. Poa L. In: Barkworth ME, Capels KM, Long S, Piep MB (Eds) Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1. Flora of North America North of Mexico, vol. 24. Oxford University Press, New York, 486-601." title="Poa L. In: Barkworth ME, Capels KM, Long S, Piep MB (Eds) Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1. Flora of North America North of Mexico, vol. 24. Oxford University Press, New York, 486 - 601." year="2007">Soreng 2007</bibRefCitation>
). This subspecies is recognizable in plastid DNA data (due to a deletion in 
<emphasis id="EE8F25E69C859270ABBEB10FA95A67EA" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">trn-TLF</emphasis>
) and nrDNA sequences as distinct from other subspecies so far evaluated (
<bibRefCitation id="FD84DDF2DA55080AE1997B6ECF792A57" author="Gillespie, LJ" journalOrPublisher="Aliso" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" publicationUrl="10.1600/0363644053661940" refId="B17" refString="Gillespie, LJ, Soreng, RJ, 2005. A phylogenetic analysis of the bluegrass genus Poa based on cpDNA restriction site data. Systematic Botany 30: 84-105. ., 10.1600/0363644053661940" title="A phylogenetic analysis of the bluegrass genus Poa based on cpDNA restriction site data. Systematic Botany 30: 84 - 105." url="10.1600/0363644053661940" year="2005">Gillespie et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="4901EF6A3B4121899698D1A69D287E2A" author="Gillespie, LJ" journalOrPublisher="Aliso" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="420 - 434" refId="B16" refString="Gillespie, LJ, Archambault, A, Soreng, RJ, 2007. Phylogeny of Poa (Poaceae) based on trn T - trn F sequence data: major clades and basal relationships. Aliso 23: 420 - 434" title="Phylogeny of Poa (Poaceae) based on trn T - trn F sequence data: major clades and basal relationships." volume="23" year="2007">2007</bibRefCitation>
). In the lower 48 states of USA, 
<taxonomicName id="C267B372DA19AD3A140AA9905913956B" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 67 - 68" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pratensis">
<emphasis id="9F3422F371368CF892B2B1C23C88D6B8" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Poa pratensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subsp. 
<emphasis id="EC8B32702DC9127854D0F84D9985DE6F" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">alpigena</emphasis>
occurs at scattered locations as far south as northern Arizona and New Mexico in alpine and subalpine habitats. This subspecies also occurs in Tierra del Fuego, Chile (see type of 
<taxonomicName id="3A254CF70BA5316D47D24EE63318B9E4" authorityName="Steud" authorityYear="1854" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oligeria">
<emphasis id="26C8191C1A9FF3D2D4AFD620A79C3D8C" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Poa oligeria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). This is the first report of this subspecies for Mexico, where it is probably best considered an interglacial period relict from glacial expansions. It can be separated from the other subspecies by its loose rhizomatous habit, small spikelets, narrow leaves, and narrow (often only slightly spreading) panicles. In North America, it usually has some scant hairs on the intermediate veins of the lemmas and on the palea keels. Several other specimens, particularly from Orizaba, approach this subspecies (see those under subsp. 
<emphasis id="EA6AF66BBA206F3A7DD96962E78E5486" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">pratensis</emphasis>
annotated as &quot;toward 
<emphasis id="60A6C6EE1A0DCA0ECB4FC6D5DEFCB320" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">alpigena</emphasis>
&quot;).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
